result.execSummary:
The defendant Tyler N. Jaenke was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess Drug Paraphernalia, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

10:15 AM Defendant Tyler N. Jaenke in court with attorney Angela Raye Olson via phone  Defendant Tyler N. Jaenke in custody via phone.  Sean Edward Froelich appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Trisha Carlson reporting via phone.  Froelich - guilty to possession of paraphanelia, concurrent with time being currently served, 30 days, with good time would be  22 1/2 days, out date would be June 23, 2020, no costs with exception of victim witness fee, state moves to quash outstanding warrant. Olson, in agreement.   Court examines defendant regarding right to waive his right to appear in person, defendant waives his right to be present in court and wishes to appear via phone.  Court accepts waiver.    Judge reviews plea waiver with defendant.    Constitutional rights explained to defendant  Exam'd re: understanding of law, penalty and rights  DEF PLEADS GUILTY to Ct. 1.  Atty Olson stipulates to factual basis.    COURT ACCEPTS PLEA, FINDS DEF FREELY, INTELLIGENTLY, KNOWINGLY & UNDERSTANDINGLY MADE AND WAIVES CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS  The court finds the defendant guilty and adjudicates defendant guilty of Ct. 1. Froelich addresses court regarding sentencing.  Olson addresses court regarding sentencing.   Court orders warrant quashed and orders 30 days in Pirece County Jail concurrent with time currently being served in Minnesota, with good time reduced to 22 1/2 days, release date June 23, 2020, Costs of $67 for victim witness surcharge.  September 1, 2022 to pay victim witness surcharge.  Appeal rights are given.  10:29 a.m.
Plea hearing on June 1, 2020 at 10:00 am.
